Your problem is, you&#39;re trying to access a variable that it&#39;s value actually dependent on the completion-handler inside of it. 

Therefore the application is giving you nil **sometimes** when the completion-handler did not trigger, on the other hand in debugging you can see a value, because the value now exists, but the problem is the complier could now be reading other lines of codes, and it doesn&#39;t know that the value is now here. 

By other words : You&#39;re trying to access some value that you fetch from somewhere, and while you&#39;re waiting that value to return, and use it properly, the compiler is now reading something else on another thread.  

What you&#39;re missing is a completion-handler that actually triggers the value of that variable when it comes from where you fetch it therefore forcing the compiler to go back and read it, when it triggers. 

&gt; **Note :** I recommend reading [this][1] article about completion-handlers and how they actually function in swift .

 
**How to fix your case:** 

Since you&#39;re using `enum`, and you want the fetching function inside the variable it self for some reason you can only fix this by creating a critical section with `DispatchSemaphores`. 

I created a small demo for you to understand how it works, and i also recommend [this][2] article. 

**Demo:**

     var name: String {
        let semaphore = DispatchSemaphore(value: 0)
        var name = &quot;no value&quot;
            DispatchQueue.global().asyncAfter(deadline: .now() + 2.0) {
                name = &quot;new Value&quot;
                semaphore.signal()
        }
        semaphore.wait()
        return name
    }
 Your code should be something like this . 

      var name: String {
            let semaphore = DispatchSemaphore(value: 0)
            var name:String?
            let uid = Auth.auth().currentUser?.uid
            Database.database().reference().child(&quot;users&quot;).child(uid!).observeSingleEvent(of: .value, with: { (snapshot) in
                if let dictionary = snapshot.value as? [String:AnyObject] {
                    name = dictionary[&quot;firstName&quot;] as? String
                    print(String(describing: name))
                    semaphore.signal() // signal when i get the new value
                }
            }, withCancel: nil)
            semaphore.wait() // wait till signal
            return name ?? &quot;Does not Work&quot;
        }

&gt; Beware this is the only way for your case, and it&#39;s not recommended, i do
&gt; recommend change your structure, because you will be freezing the
&gt; application &#39;till you get the data, and that it bad .

  [1]: https://medium.com/@nimjea/completion-handler-in-swift-4-2-671f12d33178
  [2]: https://medium.com/swiftly-swift/a-quick-look-at-semaphores-6b7b85233ddb

